The Golden State Warriors have continued to add size to their roster in the 2018-2019 season. With the addition of DeMarcus Cousins, the Warriors will be able to substitute the center position and dominate late stretches of games, unlike any other team in the NBA. Rebounds late in games are key to a team's success. I predict the Warriors will defeat Houston in 7 games and the Raptors in 5 for the 2018-2019 Championship.

The western conference champion (Golden State Warriors) is most likely to win the 2019 NBA finals. There’s pretty wide agreement among experts that they’ll win the playoffs, and they’ve set a number of records since 2014, FiveThirtyEight’s CARMELO model gives them a 49% chance at winning the title, with a 9% chance for the Rockets.

The past two NBA champions have been the Golden State Warriors (Western Conference), who this year have the number one seed in the playoffs and have the best record in the NBA. This not only gives them home-court advantage in the Western Conference Playoffs but also in the NBA Finals. Teams with home-court advantage in playoffs since 2008 have had an average win percentage of 60%. The only player to beat the Golden State Warriors and win a Finals for the Eastern Conference in the past decade has been Lebron James (two time champion with the Miami Heat and a one time champion with the Cleveland Cavaliers) but he is on the Lakers and out of playoff contention. As for the Eastern Conference heavyweights this year (Boston, Philly, Milwaukee, and Toronto) they are all plagued with Final's experience unlike the Warriors and all have never made the Finals before with their current rosters. While the Warriors roster has four years of Final experience under it. Therefore its likely that the Western Conference in particular the Warriors are going to advance to and win the NBA Finals.

The Eastern Conference division leads the Western Conference division by 38 to 32. In recent years, however, the Western conference has won 7 of the last 10 championships, three of them being the Golden State Warriors in relative succession. Barring the many extraneous variables that go into sports competitions, this pattern points to a likely chance that the Western conference will win again.
